I&#39;m elated to see someone undertake this task.   QS has an intrinsic 
beauty which is, alas, not captured in the clunky Jerome font.  I 
have been at work on a substitute myself for some time, using more 
calligraphic forms.  I too found linkages a major stumbling block.

More general thoughts later, but first:

In direct reply to your first query, I take &quot;mere&quot; to be exactly 
27-36-25. That is, it is a quickly pronounced two syllable word 
&quot;mi-er&quot;, (it&#39;s not like the French word &quot;mer,&quot; 29-25) and it is 
written with the &quot;er&quot; combination, as Read details it in the middle 
of page 10 (&quot;baker, gather, etc&quot;).  While certain dialects and 
purists may disagree here, as Read puts it &quot;any subtle distinctions 
between these sounds are neither heard not spelt successfully and 
consistently by all writers.&quot;

Now on to a larger issue: It appears to me that the issue of 
&quot;half-letters&quot; needs addressing directly at the start of your 
project. Their adoption in handwriting is designed to increase speed 
in writing and, I suspect, just because they are pretty and add to 
the visual flow of the script.

But what is being designed here is a computer font, and it does not 
have to ape the calligraphy of the hand written word.  Just as 
Medieval calligraphers drove themselves to distraction trying to ape 
with their quill pens the Roman letters carved with chisels in the 
stone on Trajan&#39;s column, and so wound up inventing the uncials, 
which took full advantage of their medium, we are now at a juncture 
in history where we are in danger of trying to ape QS calligraphy 
while punching keys on a keyboard.

It all depends on what you want to achieve: if, as in hand-done QS, 
it&#39;s all about efficiency and minimal &quot;pen lifts&quot; or keystrokes, then 
any computer alphabet that takes two keystrokes, or a key 
combination, to write one phoneme is just plain silly.  Better to use 
the 40 letters of junior QS assigned to 40 keys, while adopting only 
the abbreviated spelling conventions of Senior QS, and casting the 
half-letters to the wind.

On the other hand, if beauty and display are the main goals of 
writing QS on a computer, then the number of keystrokes be damned. 
Hail to the half-letters, and any other myriad linkages that may be 
thought of!

(If goal 2 is the one you choose, a suggestion here:  the Jerome font 
seems to have been designed in a Luddite manner, as if for a 1900 
Smith Corona, utilizing only the good old shift key for odd 
characters.  If one acknowledges that we are indeed designing for a 
computer keyboard, then we have the Command (or Apple), Option, and 
Control Keys at our disposal, all within a quarter inch of the old 
Shift key..  Thus every basic character could have 4 variations, 
instead of 1, and still reside on a logical home key.)

Another question that arises: should the sounds be assigned to the 
QWERTY arrangement of letters (another Luddite scheme if there ever 
was on, but advantageous for those that look at the keyboard) or 
should they be assigned according to phoneme frequency of use, 
requiring minimal finger movement, a la Dvorak? Could we have a 
referendum on that please? (I do have some pseudo-scientific 
information on phoneme frequency.)

And finallly, one request: in your work don&#39;t forget us Mac users 
when you do publish your font.

Good luck!







&gt;Hello all.  I am designing a replacement truetype font for Jerome.
&gt;This new font (called KINGSLEY.TTF) will include (among other things)
&gt;a more intuitive keyboard layout based on a one-to-one conversion
&gt;between the sounds of T.O. and Readscript, characters with standard
&gt;stroke widths and joining points, and kerning pairs that provide what
&gt;I perceive to be the best representation of the way Readscript was
&gt;meant to be written.
&gt;
&gt;For consistency&#39;s sake, I am currently going to be the only active
&gt;developer until the font reaches a suitable beta release state, but I
&gt;would like the input and participation of all Readscript enthusiasts
&gt;in this endeavor, such that we can truely have a font written
&gt;by-enthusiasts-for-enthusiasts and one that we can all have some
&gt;amount of personal involvement and satisfaction in.
&gt;
&gt;There are, of course, stumbling blocks to be overcome and questions
&gt;about standardization that need to be asked, so I have decided to ask
&gt;them here and now (even though the characters are only about halfway
&gt;finished).
&gt;
&gt;To kick things off, my first question to the quickscript community
&gt;regards the joining of characters to letter #25/Roe.
&gt;
&gt;As is plainly seen, the character was designed with two joining
&gt;points, both of which are incoming points and exist on the same
&gt;x-plane.  It shares the first of these properties with #22/May, and
&gt;shares both of these properties with only one other character:
&gt;#37/OUt. This introduces problems in font design when being connected
&gt;to by any characters that cross into the x-plane through or beyond
&gt;both joining sites (i.e. #&#39;s 3, 7, 10, 14, 26, 27).  When examined
&gt;further, however, one notes that most of these characters would NEVER
&gt;join to #25, except perhaps #7 or #27.  I have noticed on page 13 of
&gt;the Quickscript Manual that there seemes to be an extra character #36
&gt;in the example &quot;mere&quot; (27-36-25).  Is this really #36, or one of the
&gt;&quot;confusing linking strokes&quot; that Read talks about?  If it IS #36, is
&gt;this because of English pronunciation?
&gt;
&gt;Thanks, and I look forward to further input in participation in this
&gt;project
&gt;
